- Fri 18 Oct 2019. CMRE (Comite Multisectoriel de la Riposte a la maladie a virus Ebola)
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://mailchi.mp/bc0a6d600ff0/situation-pidmiologique-du-18-octobre-2019?e=e838b4d57b

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 17 Oct 2019:

Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 3233, of which 3117 are confirmed and 116 are probable. In total, there were 2162 deaths (2046 confirmed and 116 probable) and 1039 people cured.
- 451 suspected cases under investigation;
- 2 new probable cases, including 1 in Ituri in Mambasa and 1 in North Kivu in Kalunguta;
- 3 new confirmed cases, including 1 case in North Kivu at Oicha and 2 cases in Ituri in Mambasa;
- 2 new confirmed deaths in North Kivu, including 1 community death in North Kivu at Oicha; 3 deaths confirmed at ETC in North Kivu in Beni;
- 1 person cured out of the ETC of Mabalako;
- No health workers are among the newly confirmed cases. The cumulative number of confirmed / probable cases among health workers is 161 (5% of all confirmed / probable cases), including 41 deaths.

News
Mambau Primary School in Mambasa sensitized on handwashing
--------------------------
- The subdivision of Primary and Technical Primary Education Mambasa 1 in Ituri sensitized on Thu 17 Oct 2019 567 students from Mambau Primary School on handwashing and its importance.
- This ceremony is part of the response against the #Ebola virus disease in the Mambasa sub-coordination led by Dr. Celestin Mwanzembe. A total of 567 students, including 273 girls and 17 teachers, among whom 7 were women, were sensitized during this activity;
- The director of this school, Mr. Michel Zongoli, who congratulated this initiative taken by school authorities, asked that this kind of activities be carried out in all the schools of the territory of Mambasa;
- At the end of this awareness, 15 complete handwashing kits, a large batch of soaps, and 2 sanitation kits were given to this school by the subdivision for the sustainability of this awareness;
- "Dear Parents and Teachers: You are the important link in the Ebola response to the Ebola epidemic. Controlling the epidemic involves your commitment to supporting all pillars of the response. However, nothing can be done without information. Alert us as soon as possible so that suspicious cases are isolated and taken care of quickly. This ensures the survival of the suspect and the non-contamination of the rest of the community. Together we will defeat Ebola. Pamoja tutaweza #Ebola," said WHO monitoring team leader Dr. Thierry Kalonji after the briefing.

Description of probable cases
------------------
For the probable case of Mambasa notified on 5 Oct 2019:
- This is a 34-year-old woman who died in the Binase health zone (AS) in Brazza district of Mambasa, Ituri province. This woman was not listed as a contact and was not vaccinated;
- The date of onset of the signs is 28 Sep 2019 (with the date of exposure from 11-24 Sep [2019]) with headache and physical asthenia in Bisisa in AS Binase);
- From 28-29 Sep [2019], the woman remained untreated and continued her rural activities in Bisisa, which she left on 30 Sep [2019] to go to her home in Binase with her family. She used self-medication, and the evolution of her condition was marked by the occurrence of dysphagia, abdominal and thoracic pains, vomiting;
- She went to see a traditional health practitioner on 2 Oct [2019] and continued her "poison" treatment at home. It was on 5 Oct [2019] that the alert was launched by community relays for community-based surveillance, but the refusal to transfer to the CTE was noted. The patient was taken to her sister's home to avoid the response teams, where she died on 6 Oct 2019;
- The body was returned to her home, and the oral sample and dignified and secure burial were not made following a strong reluctance of the family;
- 47 contacts were listed around this case; the decontamination of the patient's households in Binase and Brazza and that of her neighbor were carried out on 9 Oct [2019]. A vaccination ring has been opened. She was an unspecified contact of this neighbor, her friend, who died and confirmed EVD on 22 Sep 2019. She was exposed from 14-22 Sep [2019], especially since she visited her friend at the hospital and participated in the funeral.

For the probable case of Kalunguta, notified on 4 Sep 2019:
- This is a baby girl, 2.5 years old, who died in the Tenambo health area in Kalunguta, North Kivu, living in AS Biakato Mine in Mandima, Ituri. She was not listed as a contact and was not vaccinated;
- The date of onset of the signs dates back to 26 Sep 2019, with the exposure period from 9-22 Sep 2019, due to fever and anorexia in Mandima;
- From 26 Sep-1 Oct [2019], the child was at home in Mandima; on 2 Oct [2019], she was moved with her family to Mataba in Kalunguta by motorcycle. Her clinical signs were fever, physical asthenia, vomiting, and diarrhea;
- This little girl was brought on 3 Oct [2019] to her grandfather, a traditional healer, but she died midway. The body was taken to the Ngumo / Tunavolo village, where the burial took place without the need for oral sampling or dignified and secure burial;
- She was an unlisted contact of her confirmed co-patient on 22 Sep 2019 at Bora Maisha Health Post during the period 19-21 Sep 2019;
- 15 contacts were listed around this case, including 12 family members. The decontamination of the family of the host family in Kalunguta (Mataba) was carried out on 4 Oct 2019. A ring of vaccination around the patient was realized on 13 Oct 2019, where there was a strong reluctance of the family. There was also awareness and communication about the risks of #Ebola virus disease to neighbors.

Vaccination
----------
- A satellite ring was opened in Mambasa prison around the confirmed case of 12 Oct 2019 in Nyakunde;
- Continuation of expanded ring vaccination in Mataba in the health zone of Kalunguta around the 2 confirmed cases of 12 Oct 2019;
- Continuation of the vaccination of newly recruited front-line staff (PPL) in the Kyondo (HGR Kyondo) and Kayna health zones (Bulinda health area), Musienene (Kimbulu Reference Health Center), and Butembo (Vulindi health area);
- Preparation of the vaccination of the biker taximen in the sub-coordination of Butembo, Beni, Mangina in Mabalako in North Kivu, and Mambasaen Ituri.
- Since vaccination began on 8 Aug 2018, 239 652 people have been vaccinated;
- The only vaccine to be used in this outbreak is the rVSV-ZEBOV vaccine, manufactured by the pharmaceutical group Merck, following approval by the Ethics Committee in its decision of 20 May 2018.

Monitoring at entry points
---------------------
- A dead body was intercepted at the Mususa Checkpoint in Butembo, North Kivu. This body was carried by 2 bikers disguised as agents of the response carrying personal protective equipment (PPE). These uncivics were stopped by law enforcement officers, and the body was handed over to the dignified and safe burial tteam (DHS);
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the total number of travelers checked (temperature rise) at the sanitary control points is 107 376 122;
- To date, a total of 111 entry points (PoE) and sanitary control points (PoCs) have been set up in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri to protect the country's major cities and prevent the spread of the epidemic in neighboring countries.

